<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" ?>

<chapter xml:id="ch16-line-up-please" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Line Up, Please</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Data users are often interested in questions about relationships and prediction. For
      example, those interested in athletics might want to know how the size of the fan base
      of a team is connected with attendance on game day. In this chapter, our Australian
      colleague, Robert de Graaf, introduces the techniques of linear regression, a very
      important data science tool.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-linear-regression-intro">
    <title>Finding Relationships Between Sets of Data</title>

    <p>
      Finding relationships between sets of data is one of the key aims of data science.
      The question of <q>does x influence y</q> is of prime concern for data analysts&#x2014;are
      house prices influenced by incomes, is the growth rate of crops improved by fertilizer,
      do taller sprinters run faster?
    </p>

    <p>
      The workhorse method used by statisticians to interpret data is <term>linear
      modeling</term>, which is a term covering a wide variety of methods from the
      relatively simple to very sophisticated. The basis of all these methods is the idea
      that it is possible to fit a line to a set of data points which represents the effect
      an <q>independent</q> variable is having on a <q>dependent</q> variable. The original
      ideas behind linear regression were developed by Laplace, Gauss, Galton, and Pearson.
      The biggest individual contribution was probably by Gauss, who used the procedure to
      predict movements of the other planets in the solar system.
    </p>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-afl-data">
    <title>Football or Rugby? The Australian Rules Football Example</title>

    <p>
      We can use an example to show how to use linear regression on real data. The example
      concerns attendances at Australian Rules Football matches at the Melbourne Cricket
      Ground (MCG). The variable of interest is MCG attendance. Potential explanatory, or
      independent, variables include club membership, weather on match day, date of match,
      and so on. The data are available from OzDasl at
      <url href="http://www.statsci.org/data/oz/afl.html">http://www.statsci.org/data/oz/afl.html</url>.
    </p>

    <p>
      After downloading the data, read it into R as follows:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch16-read">
      <code>
attend &lt;- read.delim("afl.txt", header=TRUE)
attach(attend)
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      With the data loaded, we can examine plots of the data before undertaking a more
      detailed analysis:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch16-plot">
      <code>
plot(MCG ~ Members,
  xlab="Combined membership of teams playing",
  ylab="MCG Match Day Attendance")
      </code>
    </program>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-linear-model">
    <title>Building a Linear Model with lm()</title>

    <p>
      We can use R to create a linear model for MCG attendance using the combined
      membership as the single explanatory variable:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch16-lm1">
      <code>
model1 &lt;- lm(MCG ~ Members - 1)
summary(model1)
abline(model1)
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      Note that in the model formula, we have added a <c>-1</c> term to the
      specification, which forces the line of best fit to pass through zero on the y axis
      when x is zero (the y-intercept is forced to be at the origin). In the present model
      that is essentially saying that if the two teams are so unpopular they don't have any
      members, no one will go to see their matches. This technique is appropriate here
      because both measures have sensible zero points, and we can logically reason that
      zero on X implies zero on Y. In most other models, particularly for survey data that
      may not have a sensible zero point, it would not be appropriate to force the best
      fitting line through the origin.
    </p>

    <p>
      The <c>summary(model1)</c> output includes the <term>r-squared value</term> (also
      known as the coefficient of determination), which represents the proportion of the
      variation in the dependent variable that is accounted for by the independent
      variable(s). An r-squared value of 1.0 would mean the X variable perfectly predicts
      Y. An r-squared of zero would indicate no predictive relationship. The r-squared of
      0.8847 in this example means that the Combined Members variable accounts for 88.47%
      of the MCG attendance variable&#x2014;an excellent result.
    </p>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-multiple-regression">
    <title>Adding Another Independent Variable</title>

    <p>
      Some of the teams in the AFL are from interstate (outside Victoria), and their
      supporters would need to make a significant interstate journey to see their team play
      at the MCG. We can create a binary coded variable to indicate whether the away team
      is interstate:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch16-ifelse">
      <code>
away.inter &lt;- ifelse(Away=="WC" |
  Away=="Adel" |
  Away=="Syd" |
  Away=="Bris", 1, 0)
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      Now we can include this new variable in a two-predictor model:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch16-lm2">
      <code>
model2 &lt;- lm(MCG ~ Members + away.inter - 1)
summary(model2)
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      The r-squared value is now 0.9246, which is quite a bit higher than the 0.8847 that
      we observed in the previous model. In this new model, the two independent variables
      working together account for 92.46% of the dependent variable.
    </p>

    <p>
      To determine whether each predictor is an important contributor to the prediction,
      examine the <q>t value</q> in the model output. As a rule of thumb, if this t value
      has an absolute value larger than about 2, you can be assured that the independent
      variable is contributing to the prediction. In this example <c>Members</c> has a
      t value of 21.257 and <c>away.inter</c> has a t value of <m>-4.545</m> (both are
      well above 2 in absolute value).
    </p>

  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ch16">
    <title>Chapter Challenge</title>
    <exercise xml:id="ex-ch16-challenge">
      <statement>
        <p>
          We intentionally ignored some of the output of these regression models. It would
          be quite valuable for you to understand those missing parts. In particular, we
          ignored the <q>p-values</q> associated with the t-tests on the slope/B-weight
          estimates and we also ignored the overall F-statistic reported at the very bottom
          of the output. Research these concepts online.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </exercises>

